{"id":"1312.1092","submitter":"Alessio Avella","authors":"Alessio Avella, Marco Gramegna, Alexander Shurupov, Giorgio Brida,\n  Maria Chekhova, Marco Genovese","title":"Separable Schmidt modes of a non-separable state","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 89, 023808 (2014)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.89.023808","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Two-photon states entangled in continuous variables such as wavevector or\nfrequency represent a powerful resource for quantum information protocols in\nhigher-dimensional Hilbert spaces. At the same time, there is a problem of\naddressing separately the corresponding Schmidt modes. We propose a method of\nengineering two-photon spectral amplitude in such a way that it contains\nseveral non-overlapping Schmidt modes, each of which can be filtered\nlosslessly. The method is based on spontaneous parametric down-conversion\n(SPDC) pumped by radiation with a comb-like spectrum. There are many ways of\nproducing such a spectrum; here we consider the simplest one, namely passing\nthe pump beam through a Fabry-Perot interferometer. For the two-photon spectral\namplitude (TPSA) to consist of non-overlapping Schmidt modes, the crystal\ndispersion dependence, the length of the crystal, the Fabry-Perot free spectral\nrange and its finesse should satisfy certain conditions. We experimentally\ndemonstrate the control of TPSA through these parameters. We also discuss a\npossibility to realize a similar situation using cavity-based SPDC.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Dec 2013 10:09:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-04-23"}
